defaultQ92 default&#xa0; 
defaultGraham Stringer:default The fifth report has been criticised for underestimating the role of solar cycles and the role of cosmic rays in cloud formation. Do you think that is a fair criticism of the IPCC report?
defaultProfessor Lindzendefault: Yes. You are dealing with something that is very uncertain. It is 
defaultpretty 
defaultclear that actual solar variability is very small. We now have satellite data, which shows it is a fraction of 
defaulta
default watt per metre squared. On the other hand, there is now some experimental evidence—and there has been hypothesis for decades—that things like cosmic rays, which vary quite a lot, have an influence on the formation of cloud condensation nuclei, which can change the brightness of clouds and also the ability to form sometimes. This can amplify the effect of solar variability by a large factor. That is an unknown at this moment. The IPCC not only did not include it but it may not have any way of including it at the moment.
